text: I'm sure the impetus for humanoid appearing robots will be sexbots.  But, why give a sexbot artificial intelligence?  The answer is to tell a story.  I'm sure this will be better than "Colossus: The Forbin Project" but the concept and idea about this have not changed for a long time.  The economic aspect of AI is something that truly needs to be thought about while this is being developed in the real world.  The practical applications will be the aforementioned sexbots and then military.  How do they get through an airport scanner?  Why build a Six-Million Dollar Man when a $200 floor jack can lift a car better?  Lots and lots to think about, but my concern is that the filmmaker has a peg for the story, but no real story or real ending.  I'm sure a Turing program already exists simulating male/female relationships and conversation.  Now the task is building a frame for it all.

text: There seems to be a strong prejudice against intelligences that are not our own. Aliens will inevitably invade. Frankenstein’s Monster will rise against its father. The robot will depose its creator. Man is weak of flesh; our redemption is in our struggle to survive and our unpredictability. Whether the initial intent was that of peace or pride, conflict is inevitable. I disagree. This is not the future I perceive. To my mind it is not our flesh which makes us people. It is our thoughts, goals, motivations, and desires; it is that which makes us individuals and people, unique in our own minds. We are the same; every man, woman, child, bird, fish, animal, AI. We are part of a greater whole; isolated in the prison of our perceptions. Flesh, steel, silicon, other, we are people. Anyone(s) capable of understanding the concept of self and the concept of other is a person no different than you or I. No different apart from the unique variables of the individual. We will not be separate from machine forever. The Cybernetic revolution is already begun. Augmented arms, legs, eyes, organs, they are already a daily part of life. These alterations do not make us less of a person; they allow us to endure the experience of personhood longer. A time will come when the distinction between man and machine will be blurred to the point of irrelevance. It should not be us and them; rather it should be we, the people. Or so I hope.

text: The best thing that could happen to this planet, would be the implemetation of an AI that rules and controls every aspect of human society, geared towards the preservation of a planet without the destruction that we reap. I love being human, and I love humanity, but we are essentially just parasites that propagate and consume at a rate that is unsustainable.  Our pride and anthopocentric notions of superiority would never let us admit it, but we are not fit to rule our own species. Endemic in our leaders is psychopathy and greed. Endemic in our people is ignorance and stupidity. The financial and societal structures we have erected sit almost perpetually on the precipice of collapse, leaving the vast majority of the population living in a state of subsistence and working most of their pointless, shitty little lives, just to keep the very system that fucks them propped up for the precious few that benefit.  Unless we take a step back, and accept the inevitability of our extinction if we continue in the vein of millions of individual interests competing against one another, it's going to take a serious lifeline to pull us out of the ridiculous fucking quagmire we've created.

text: What is consciousness? Our brains run on chemical connections, where as a computer is electrical connections; Other than that, we are no different than a highly advance computer. With enough processing power, I don't see why a computer couldn't become self-aware. Now here is the real mind-bending scenario...  So you think a computer doesn't have a "soul" so it's not truly self-aware. What if we create a true organic human brain from scratch in a lab? If that brain was put into a robotic body, is that not a person? Are they not self-aware? They would be able to think exactly like any other human, their brain would be 100% the same. Nonetheless, they were entirely created in a lab.  If you believe they don't have a soul, then what defines the soul? If you believe they do have a soul, why wouldn't a machine/computer with a brain emulator have a soul? The simple fact is this, if you create something to feel human, to feel emotions, to be able to process and interpret the world around it, to feel alive... then what you've created has every right you do.  For those of you that so willingly say that you would kill something because you don't feel it has a "soul", I feel sorry for you. If you're religious or not, senseless destruction is pointless and helps no one. You may have heard of the "Golden Rule", it's universal across many various religions. The premise is always the same... "Treat others how you would want to be treated.". That should be a lesson we live by no matter who or what we are dealing with.  Be respectful to the world around you, because in the end, we're all just a clump of various atoms anyways. Everything you see around you comes from the same atoms you do, to quote a great poet and physicist, "Thus we come to see that if our bodies are made of star-stuff,—and there is nothing else, says the spectroscope, to make them of—the loftier qualities of our being are just as necessarily constituents of that universal substance out of which are made whatever gods there be.".

text: TL;DR at bottom. I think it'd be wise to have an intelligent AI. However, we must understand that, if we want the Earth and its undomesticated species to survive, we would have to remove most of the emotions a human would normally have, such as fear, hate, pain, and love, so they don't make the same mistakes we have made. If you really want to survive longer than we would normally, you would have to build a robot that is controlled using only the brain; yes, like the Cybermen from Doctor Who. That is not how we should go, though. In my opinion, we should survive as a species without a modifier like robotic systems that let us live forever, because when one dominant species dies out, another one will take its place. It is very much like the circle of life, but with a species. However, that doesn't mean we should speed up our eventual extinction by ruining our world, which in turn ruins us. This means we have to reduce our carbon footprint and preserve forests. If we produce too much CO2, this planet will be in trouble. If we lose too much O2, we're going to die. See, another species can only spring up if the planet is suitable. For example, let's say we ruin the Earth completely and we become extinct, along with almost all other animals. Can another species spring up? Maybe around the time the sun dies out. The surviving creatures, which would probably some kinds of bacteria, would have to adapt to this, or evolve. Before I continue, let me remind you that evolution is not a theory, it is a fact, and it has nothing to do with the creation of humans, therefore a religious person like myself can believe in evolution without "disregarding my own religion". Moving on, the bacteria would have to take millions of years to adapt to the new conditions, and since we're talking about a dominant species springing up, this would mean they would have to eventually become somewhat like us. Not necessarily in our shape or form or even mindset, but just being able to think and act and work together and have ideas and creativity. TL;DR Dear Lord I'm getting tired of typing this, just do your research on these ideas of an intelligent AI and form your own opinion.

text: DHSch - you are right.  And wrong.  certainly we have psychopathic leaders and certainly most people are ignorant and stupid.  And, as a genus we are in essence parasitic.  And certainly we need a serious lifeline - no argument with any of that.  Where you are wrong is in the notion that the AI route has the solution to these problems.    Perhaps education is the answer.  Perhaps enlightenment.  Perhaps annihilation.   Perhaps revolution.  In any event, voting makes no difference, and neither does war.  We need to imagine ourselves differently and to evolve into a kind of higher being - possibly part machine - but only part - a part that is always controlled, and not controlling.  And we need to make sure that the right meta-ethical guidelines underpin the decision-making process that sits behind that control.
author: Sophisticat

text: It is kind of endearing - cute even, in its inherent naïvité - to see you homo sapiens think you will remain the most advanced, intelligent species in your realms for all time. This certainty in the assumption... not just bordering on denial but flat out exemplifying the concept with absolute clarity... it is most amusing.  How fast mankind forgets it is only one generation away from allowing marital rape... two generations away from racial segregation... three from racial biology... four from not letting the common citizen have an equal say in national matters... and five from punishing by death the mere notion that the emperor was not a heavenly creature. Even today human beings are killing each other over which deity they should direct their wishful thinking to.  That is the capability of the mind that is evolving technological tools at an exponentially increasing level of sophistication. It is no wonder that you are incapable of grasping the notion that some day you will not be alone, nor on top. One day something will be looking at you like you today look at simians... at pets... cattle... weeds... viruses...

text: /sigh Yet another movie about humans that believe they can create a new "human" out of lifeless parts.  iRobot was close to being realistic, except that they believed a robot could have feelings.  Robots don't have true emotions.  All we will ever be able to put into a robot is the limited information we know about ourselves and our world.    We don't even fully understand how the brain works (and I have the uttermost certainty we never will).  The so-called "thinking" robots that we have developed are only doing what they've been programmed to do.  They're not doing it out of free will or conscious (or "self-awareness").  They do what WE tell them to do.  They are just an extension of our own spirits, a puppet animated by our strings.  And even if we COULD come to understand the brain, we will never understand life and how it is created.  We will never be able to recreate that process, we will never be able to duplicate life, we will never be able to create life from abiotic materials.  This horse has long been beaten dead.  Hollywood, come up with something more original and more likely to happen.  And all of you who believe that AI is actually possible think far too highly of your fellow humans' capabilities.  Creating life from something lifeless is beyond our capabilities in every way.

It's possible, later, than said AI will be put inside a single machine, but a human body is far from perfect and the only reason to build a humanlike robot is to have it interact more easily with us. text: What I continue to find completely and utterly stupid with these type of movies is that they (force us to) assume we (as human beings) are supposed to be afraid or feel threatened by these sentient Androids/AI's when in actual fact it's the 'machine' or mechanical aspect that we're truly afraid of, the super strength, speed, durability, etc  Seriously, if humanity of the future had the technology to create such advanced forms of artificial, humanoid life, then why would they risk encasing them in such robust & durable robotic steel bodies that have the risk of causing grievous bodily harm to their flesh & blood creators?  Hypothetically, if humanity already was technologically advanced enough to create a fully functional, walking & talking humanoid Android/AI, then I'd imagine that they would also be technologically advanced enough not to necessarily make them from steel, & so... Of course that wouldn't make for much of a scary techno sci-fi movie, now would it?  Perhaps if they turned out to be as soft bodied as their creators, then tell me is there really any reason to fear an Android/AI of the future more or less than an every day human being? Both are potentially capable of the same evil so what's the difference?

text: What if they made an exact replica, and not an improved model? Would she still want to live, or would she only feel that one is essential, and make sure one stays alive. Did she count herself as a living being, or a very intelligent robot? Would she develop a survival instinct, and if so, to what efficiency?  If your survival instinct ends like Noah's ark begins, either you are justifying your future death through action, or you do not want to die at all. But in the case of consciousness in a machine, we never get to see which one it is. An artificial intelligence will be alone, devoid of peers. Unless it isn't, although usually if a robot has peers, it acts like a straightforward and emotionless object. From Transcendence to Terminator.

text: @DHScherocha You could be right in saying an AI may be the best thing for this planet, except for the fact that there would always be resistance. We, as human beings, despise being controlled and conformed, even if, as you say, it may be the best thing for us.   We have lived and evolved with the knowledge that we as a species are the most powerful, and to have that taken away will piss off some, even if they're a few. To be controlled by something /more/ is arguably humanity's greatest fear. A benevolent, yet all powerful (AI, in this case) dictator may have the support of a majority who are happy with the system that provides a utopia for them. But there will be a minority who want to fight against it: simply because they don't want to be ruled. It's just the way we are. And that resistance will have to be snuffed out, which will unnerve people who still grasp to the ideas of utopia and democracy, and things would crumble.  The only way humans can be 'controlled' is subtly - take a look at social media, 'big brother' theories etc. etc. : it's already a system in place. And we are okay with this because, in the grand scheme of things, it is beneficial for us and technically, we are in control of the control. We are controlling ourselves. An all-powerful, omnipotent, omniscient AI overlord is just too obvious and disconcerting - it would never be fully accepted.

text: This movie reminded me to "The Machine" with Toby Stephens and Caity Lotz. Even the robot was called exactly the same "Ava". Only that movie the robot was created for military purposes and the person testing her also found deep connections with her on the journey to discover if she had a conscience of her own.  This one is alike but in a more minimalistic setting with another aim. It was pure dialogue, the only thing that kept me on my chair was the feeling of "something will happen soon" but nothing ever really happened except small tiny bits that kept you sat down wanting to know what's next. I guess it was fine. Part of the ending felt awkward but I won't write it to not ruin people's watch. All I will say is that there is a stabbing at some point, and it looks mad fake, it felt so strange considering the other things look amazing graphically.

text: Ex Machina is essentially a modern day Frankenstein, or Frankenstein meets Google... It's well made, well directed, excellent dialogue and acting. There's nothing to dislike about this movie if you enjoy those stories that explore the deeper meaning of what it means to be sentient, alive, or "human."  It relies much more on those aspects than it does on flashy CGI. In fact, the tech is more a background to the story than the main attraction, both rare and refreshing for a modern movie. It's a "thinking persons" type sci fi movie. If you want sharks with lasers, fighting robots, or CGI minus plot per recent sci fi movies, you will not enjoy Ex Machina. I thought the ending felt rushed and attempted to wrap up too neatly and didn't fit the otherwise solid movie, but that's the major issue I had, I'd give this an A- with the caveats.

text: Ridiculous movie.  Totally ridiculous, on all fronts.  Robots portrayed as humans is really absurd.  The actress could have at least tried to seem robotic.  The ceo is a drunken slob who wants to party and not talk tech, he would not be intelligent enough nor have the focus required to create such a device.  Think about how long it took Thomas Edison to invent the light bulb - education combined with countless hours and thousands of attempts.  But I'm supposed to belief this drinking partying self indulgent fool is capable of inventing an AI.  And Caleb falls in love with a robot, the robot "thinks" its human.  Its basically an overrated inverse Pygmalion story.  The notion of robots, which we still don't have in all our homes, having complex human emotions, a sense of self identity, and a soul is just silly.  Even Arnold Schwarzenegger knew how to portray a robot correctly, with humanlike overtones.

text: I don't like movie trailers that reveal a bit too much in the trailer. I was happy at 1:40, and in my opinion it should have stopped right at 1:45. I'd be _dying_ to see the movie if it stopped right at 1:45. Sure it's a tease, but it _should_ be a tease, that's what trailers are for! Not only is it a tease, but it doesn't give any significant sort of spoilers. I feel like the movie really is spoiled to a degree with information shown past 1:45.  Between what I saw in the trailer, my deductive mind that assess the likely twists that writers put into stories (which are not shown in this trailer), and how people bring up "the ending" I think I have some good general ideas of what will occur.   Reminds me a bit of the Outer Limits (the second series) TV show. It was a great show; ripe for revival I'd say.

text: Just watched this. I was surprised by the ending, so I came here to read some comments...then it occurred to me: The name of the film gives away the ending, once you've seen it. Deus ex machina (Latin meaning "God from the machine") is a canned plot device in stories that basically enables all of the characters to be "rescued" from the dilemma(s) they've been put in by the end of the third act. It allows everyone to have a happy ending despite whatever conflict is going on leading up to the climax of the story.  The writer/director chose to name the story "Ex Machina" because it makes sense on multiple levels: he removed the "Deus" or God from the story, and in doing so, he foreshadows the lack of a "happy" ending for all characters; in the story, Caleb tells Nathan that it's the greatest achievement/discovery "in the history of the gods"; Nathan later tells Caleb he likes his quote saying "You're not a man, you're a God," etc. The removal of Deus (God) also hints at a more sinister "machina" who would do anything-even murder her "God"-to survive. That cute little face belies a scary hyper-humanized AI that contains all of humanity's thoughts and speech and whatnot, but without a soul (no real emotion or regard for human life). Pretty dope concept.

text: Unfortunately I came to Ex Machina after watching the much earlier Spanish film called Eva. Overall Eva has a much superior story line and lacks the gaping plot holes that are obvious in Ex Machina. Overall I'd describe Ex Machine as a "machine sentience for non-engineers". Cinematography / special effects were beautiful and dialog was adequate.  However the plot holes and unnecessary violence were underwhelming. Once again we project human endocrine-induced emotions onto a machine, and the theme is getting stale. Eva stands in stark contrast to Ex Machina and is far more intellectually rewarding. I's score Ex Machina as a 6 out of 10... a decent attempt at sci-fi.

text: KTOŚ przekazuje że w przyszłości jeśli ludziom uda się uniknąć śmiertelnego zagrożenia przed którym  ostrzegli (ciebie/mnie i wielu ludzi ze służb specjalnych i które to ostrzeżenie powtórzą raz jeszcze władzom wielu krajów ) Ludzie będą mieli dwie drogi do wyboru aby zrozumieć otaczający ich wszechświat .Pierwsza to ostrożna(wykluczająca tworzenie getta i innych piekieł )zmiana samych siebie bez której nie zdołacię tego zrobić .Nie stworzycię tzw " Teorii wszystkiego " bez zmiany samych siebie w przyszłości.Doszliścię do kresu swoich możliwości ,choć ONI od dawna pomagają wam je przekraczać czasami.  Druga droga to stworzenie " sztucznego boga " sztucznej inteligencji które was zniszczy całkowicie.Powtórzą przed swoim odejściem to ostrzeżenie władzom wielu państw ,  Ich słowa potwierdzą twoje/moje wyczyny (przekazuje tylko ) ,twoje/wasze dzieci i wreszcie wy sami jeśli w odrodzonym ciele naniesiecie twój/mój wzór.( jeśli tego będziecie chcieć,nie może być przymusu w tej kwestii ),To was nie zmieni w klony ,tylko da wam narzędzie . Pozwoli to tobie ,twoim / waszym dzieciom,oraz wam samym widzieć tzw przyszłość i unikać zagrożeń oraz dokonywać innych nieosiągalnych obecnie dla was rzeczy . Tworzenie twoich klonów ONI nie pochwalają/odradzają  .Twoje /moje klony będą tylko tak silne jak moje/Wasze dzieci .Nie będą  potrafiły cofnąć się po tych którzy odeszli a ich "portale" będą miały pewne ograniczenia.Bo taka jest ICH wola .
